es our understanding of the role of religion in social movements and demonstrates the nonviolent power of religious groups to address social injustices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFaith-based human servicesxUnited States. 0aFaith-based human serviceszUnited States. 0aReligion and justice. 0aReligion and statexUnited States. 0aReligion and statezUnited States. 0aSocial justicexReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aamerican activism.  aamerican religions.  acalifornia.  achicago.  achristian activism.  achristian americans.  achristianity.  acivil liberties.  adeath.  ahuman dignity.  aimmigrant rights.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration and emigration.  aislam.  ajewish activism.  ajudaism.  alabor rights.  alatino immigrants.  amajor world religions.  amigration.  amuslim activism.  amuslim americans.  anonviolent protest.  apolitical.  areligion.  areligious activism.  areligious groups.  asocial injustice.  asocial movements.  aunited states of america.  aus mexican border.  aviolence.  axenophobia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094244840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520942448/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles